description.plain: Jeremih Felton, better known under his mononym Jeremih, is an American rapper and recording artist born in Chicago on July 17, 1987. He has collaborated with many other renowned artists and producers, such as 50 Cent, J. Cole, YG, Chris Brown, Chance The Rapper, Nicki Minaj, Future, Ty Dolla $ign, French Montana DJ Khaled, and Shlohmo. He has so far released 3 albums. His latest one, released in 2015, is called Late Nights and peaked at number 42 on the Billboard 200, selling 11,000 copies. His radio-friendly voice and style of production makes Jeremih a sought-after guest feature for a lot of artists, getting paid roughly $200,000 for a feature.

songs.title: Planez

description.plain:
Originally titled as “Planes” and released as the second single from Jeremih’s third LP Late Nights, “Planez” is a tribute to joining the “mile-high club.”

The song title came from producer Vinylz. Jeremih kept the working title that Vinylz had originally given the beat.

Jeremih originally performed this song live with Chance The Rapper in 2014 (and would later be released as a remix) , but he instead called on J. Cole for the album version.

songs.title: Don’t Tell ’Em

description.plain:
The first single from Jeremih’s 3rd studio album Late Nights is a club anthem that dominated the charts through the summer and fall 2014. Jeremih told Billboard that he was inspired to write his own #1 single after “Show Me” – a song he co-wrote – went #1 on the Rap Airways.

Despite this song’s success, there’s no music video to go with. Jeremih takes the blame for that; he admitted to Billboard that a video was scheduled but he didn’t show up for the shoot. He neglected to explain why.

The song samples vocals from the classic Euro-dance record “Rhythm is a Dancer”“ which DJ Mustard, Jeremih & YG flip into a R&B/Hip-Hop club smash.



Several remixes and covers of the song have since been released including an official remix, a UK remix and Pop singer Lorde performed a cover version for the BBC 1 Radio 1 Live Lounge.

Jeremih explained the making of the song on The Tonight Show with Jimmy Fallon, revealing that he offered the song to 2 Chainz but decided to work with YG when Chainz asked too much for a verse.

songs.title: ​oui

description.plain:
“Oui” is French for “yes"—in Jeremih’s ode to romantic devotion, he makes a pun based on the word’s English language homophone, "we.”

In order to have “we"—a couple—you need two people, or "you” and “I.” And to spell the word “oui,” you also need a “u” and “i.”

“Oui” was produced by Needlz and his protégé Donut. The beat features an electronic harp melody and trap-influenced drums. Donut recalled producing the original beat:

I think I was in Philly at the time ‘cause this song is like two or three years old. I found this eight-bar loop that was really cool but it wasn’t doing the notes that I wanted it to so I chopped it up.

While the song doesn’t credit any samples, fans have noted its similarity to “Marcia Baila,” a 1986 track by French pop duo Rita Mitsouko, as well as the Fairy Fountain theme from video game The Legend of Zelda.

The song’s vocals mix Jeremih’s coversational style with traditional doo-wop and R&B inflections. The bridge features an interpolation of a melody from Shai’s “If I Ever Fall In Love,” a number one R&B hit from 1992.

“Oui” was the fourth single off Jeremih’s third studio album Late Nights. The singer debuted the lyrics exclusively on Genius on October 29, 2015, one day before the song was released. The song became a top 10 R&B hit in the Spring of 2016.

description.plain:
Jeremih once stated:

I can make a great sex song anytime I want, without even saying a body part, without saying anything that would be omitted on the radio. Somehow I’ve just been given that ability

Agree or not with this statement, it’s undeniable that on this specific song he did it well. Jeremih brings out another good love-fuck song with only a couple of swear words, proving his skills.

Without using NSFW language, Jeremih teams up with Ty Dolla $ign for his third song on his third studio release Late Nights: The Album, setting up the perfect atmosphere to make love.

Agree or not with this statement, it’s undeniable that on this specific song he did it well. Jeremih brings out another good love-fuck song with only a couple of swear words, proving his skills.

Without using NSFW language, Jeremih teams up with Ty Dolla $ign for his third song on his third studio release Late Nights: The Album, setting up the perfect atmosphere to make love.

songs.full_title: I Think of You by Jeremih (Ft. Big Sean & Chris Brown)
songs.title: I Think of You
songs.title_with_featured: I Think of You (Ft. Big Sean & Chris Brown)

description.plain:
On “I Think of You,” Jeremih recruits Chris Brown and Big Sean for a nostalgic love song dedicated to their women. The track samples Montell Jordan’s 1999 song “Get It On Tonite.”

“I Think of You” was released as the lead single from Jeremih’s fourth studio album, Later That Night. The track marks the third collaboration between Breezy and Jeremih, with the duo working together on DJ Khaled’s “Do You Mind” and “Hold You Down.” Jeremih and Big Sean are frequent collaborators, with the pair working together on “Living Single,” “Light,” “Royalty,” “All That Lady” and “Wanna Be Cool.”

songs.title: Paradise

description.plain:
“Paradise” is the final song on Jeremih’s 2015 album Late Nights.

The Mick Schultz-produced track gained traction in January 2017, after Kim Kardashian released a video montage of herself along with Kanye West, and their two children, North and Saint—a slightly altered version of “Paradise” plays in the background.

https://twitter.com/KimKardashian/status/816465798755545088?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw

Schultz tells Genius that Kanye personally reached out for the song’s raw files, without specifying his intentions.

If you watch the video, you can hear Jeremih’s verses aren’t on there, [Kanye] cut in and out from the original to just the track with the background vocals.

“Paradise"—which features only piano and vocals, no drums—was inspired by The Beatles. Jeremih told FADER he "wanted to do something different. I wanted to show people I could just reflect, in a ballad format.”

songs.full_title: Royalty by Jeremih (Ft. Big Sean & Future)
songs.title: Royalty

description.plain:
Just hours after the lyrics première and release of “Oui”, Jeremih returned with yet another single from his third album Late Nights.

The club banger sees Jeremih team up with Future and Def Jam label mate Big Sean on the advantages of being rich and famous in the club, something the trio are all too familiar with. The song was first teased by Big Sean during an interview with Angie Martinez, speculating it may have been recorded during their time on Act 3 of the Forest Hills Drive tour.

songs.full_title: Try Me (Left Cheek) by Jeremih (Ft. Travis Scott)
songs.title: Try Me (Left Cheek)

description.plain:
“Try Me” is a leaked collaboration between Jeremih and Travis Scott. The song was given the name “Left Cheek” by DJ SpinKing, and is often known, albeit incorrectly, as “Left Cheek, Right Cheek”.

Two versions of the song exist: Travis' version which features more vocals from Travis himself, and this version created for DJ SpinKing which features additional production from Hitmaka and more vocals from Jeremih.

Jeremih previewed an early version “Try Me” in April 2015 via Snapchat, before giving it to Travis who previewed his version on November 18, 2015, at the Filmore as part of  The Weeknd’s The Madness Tour. Fans speculated that the song would appear on Travis' then-forthcoming album, Birds in the Trap Sing McKnight. The song didn’t make the cut, however, DJ SpinKing later said that the song would appear on his mixtape, For The Culture. Again, the song didn’t make the cut as Travis took the song back.

This version of the song leaked online on September 13, 2018. One of the song’s producers, Vinylz, who had previously teased releasing Travis' version of the song took to Twitter to emphasise that this leaked version is not the final version of the song.

“773 Love” is a tribute to Jeremih’s home city of Chicago. It’s about a booty call, where its title alludes to the region and calling code of Chicago.

It’s worth noting that this was his first delivery since “Down on Me”, which had came out two years before.

The Weeknd’s contribution to this remix came from his Christmas remix of the song, while Chance The Rapper and Young Thug contribute original verses. Chance previously remixed “Planes” from the same album, but J. Cole’s version made it as the opening track.

songs.title: Late Nights

description.plain: The title track and arguable thesis statement of Jeremih’s Late Nights saga, his self-produced effort tackles nothing other than a late night after a show. If “Late Nights” is the opener, then Late Nights: The Album’s “Paradise” is the closer that shows what happens after the party. The warm production oozes seduction, as do his vocals, and it stands out as one of the most traditional R&B offerings on the mixtape.

songs.full_title: Giv No Fuks by Jeremih (Ft. Migos)
songs.title: Giv No Fuks

description.plain:
“Giv No Fuks” is the sixth song off Jeremih’s critically acclaimed Late Nights album. With help from two-thirds of Migos, Jeremih lets loose and explores the wild side of stardom, as Jeremih navigates a world of drug experimentation, infidelity, fast foreign cars, and one-night stands. Quavo and Takeoff add a hint of trap to the soundscape with their verses while using their feature to remind us once more that Offset is not free.

The Tariq Beats instrumental samples “Ophelia” by André Popp. The sample used in “Give No Fuks” is taken just after the 0:08 mark in “Ophelia”.

https://youtu.be/auaPJIGTBOo

This song is sung by Jeremih to his lover, reminiscing on previous romantic experiences and verbalizing his dedication to her.

body.plain:
Keen fans will note that, unlike all other cities and countries seen in the tracklist of Jeremih’s Late Nights: Europe mixtape, Dubai is not in Europe. Jeremih addressed this on Twitter, explaining that Dubai, UAE (Asia) was where he had a show right before the Europe tour started.

songs.full_title: Tonight Belongs To U! by Jeremih (Ft. Flo Rida)
songs.title: Tonight Belongs To U!
songs.title_with_featured: Tonight Belongs To U! (Ft. Flo Rida)

description.plain:
“Tonight Belongs To U!” is the third single from Jeremih’s yet to be released third LP, Late Nights: The Album. It is a drastic change from his previous two urban-sounding singles, (“Don’t Tell ‘Em” and “Planes”) as he sings over a dance-pop beat.

Jeremih announced that Flo Rida would be on the album in August 2014 during an interview with HotNewHipHop.

songs.full_title: The Crib by Jeremih (Ft. Chi Hoover & G Herbo)
songs.title: The Crib
songs.title_with_featured: The Crib (Ft. Chi Hoover & G Herbo)

description.plain:
“The Crib” breaks the mixtape’s concept by being the standalone track not named after a European city.

Instead, Jeremih and G Herbo choose to pay homage to their hometown of Chicago while still keeping the mixtape’s sexual themes intact by detailing their escapades in different parts of the city.

songs.full_title: Break Up to Make Up by Jeremih
songs.title: Break Up to Make Up

description.plain:
This was the third single taken from American R&B vocalist Jeremih’s self-named debut collection.

Jeremih disclosed to This is RnB how he concocts the thoughts for his melodies: “In some cases I have an idea in my psyche, here and there I definitely know where I need to go. Yet, ordinarily generally, we basically start without any preparation with the snap of my fingers. While making a track, I started to hear as though the music addresses me, as insane as that sounds. (Snickers). I went with what the beats advised me, and that is the means by which we had the option to take out a ton of the records, and basically have the beats match a ton with the manner in which I was singing in light of the fact that in any event, when it came to drops. For example, in ‘Separate to Make Up’ with the birds trilling in the second refrain coming in, you know, it went inseparably. We’re doing essentially everything naturally, so that is the way it was made.”

songs.title: Belgium (Get Down)

description.plain: “Belgium (Get Down)” is the second track off Jeremih’s 2016 tour-inspired mixtape Late Nights: Europe. The song is a hook-driven venture that succeeds off its bouncy, oft-ominous production while Jeremih focuses on his vocals vibes above lyricism. In naming Late Nights: Europe Stereogum’s Album of the Week, Tom Breihan called “Belgium (Get Down)” the best song off the tape.

description.plain:
In the early hours of Wednesday morning (October 22nd), Krept tweeted the picture below, speculating a song was in the mix, and the end product came a lot earlier than many would have thought. That night at the 2014 MOBO awards, the duo joined Jeremih on stage to debut their remix to his club banger “Don’t Tell Em”, adding their own flavour to the smash hit.



Update: The official audio was released on November 11th.

And if the song itself isn’t enough, visuals could be on the way soon!

Over raucous, bell-driven production by Mike Will Made It, he takes account of his status as one of R&B’s brightest voices, and how that has afforded him a life of temptation.

songs.title: Talk Too Much*

description.plain:
“Talk Too Much” is a short leaked track by singer, Jeremih. Due to its length, it’s likely that the song was a reference/demo that was never returned to.

The song was leaked by Music Mafia on March 20, 2018. They were also responsible for leaking Jeremih’s PARTYNEXTDOOR collaboration, “Don’t Tell Me”.

The beat was produced by DJ Mustard who has worked with Jeremih on songs like “Don’t Tell ‘em”.

songs.full_title: Money Do by Jeremih (Ft. Gucci Mane)
songs.title: Money Do

description.plain:
Jeremih and Gucci Mane team up for “Money Do.”
The long, confusing road to Jeremih’s Late Nights: The Album continues today with the release of “Money Do.” As we’ve documented, Jeremih seems to pull us in a different direction every time he drops a supposed-Late Nights cut, and this remains true here.
Last we heard from him we got the pop/dance-heavy “Tonight Belongs To U!” featuring Flo-Rida. Today, he goes a more trap route with an appearance from GuWop and a minimalistic beat. He sing-raps on this one, and it could simply be a throwaway given how short it is.
